Exploratory Data Analysis of CPE’s Dallas Policing Dataset of 2016


INTRODUCTION

The data provided includes information regarding crime incidences that happened in Dallas, Texas, the United States, as well as data about the officer, subject, place, race, date, time, method of force used, and other metrics for the entire 2016 year.

The Centre for Policing Equity (CPE) generated a data set that focuses on policing in Dallas, Texas in 2016. This report’s goal is to study that data set. The goal of the CPE is to use cutting-edge analysts to make policing diagnoses that shed light on police behaviour and offer meaningful advice to police forces.This set of data includes 2384 incidents and information on 47 factors.The data pertains to 2016, which runs from January through December.This research breaks down and explores patterns in policing behaviour using significant data visualisation.

#Reading the dataset 
dallas<-read.csv("37-00049_UOF-P_2016_prepped.csv")

#In the below line of code we are to remove the 1 row which is having some random and null values,So we cannot consider those values.
dallas<-dallas[-1,]
#Date and Month Conversion:
dallas$INCIDENT_DATE <- as.Date(dallas$INCIDENT_DATE, format = "%m/%d/%Y")
dallas$INCIDENT_DATE <- gsub("00","20",dallas$INCIDENT_DATE)
dallas$INCIDENT_DATE <- as.Date(dallas$INCIDENT_DATE, format = "%Y-%m-%d")
dallas$INCIDENT_TIME <- format(strptime(dallas$INCIDENT_TIME, "%I:%M:%S %p"), "%H:%M:%S")
dallas$INCIDENT_MONTH <- months(as.Date(dallas$INCIDENT_DATE))
dallas$INCI_MONTH <-format(dallas$INCIDENT_DATE,"%m")

Force Applied: Type

Relationship between Subject Race and the Force Used


According to the two graphs below, verbal command is the type of force used while determining a subject’s race and gender.The force types are broken down by subject gender and race in the graphs. Men and women are given verbal commands more frequently, and men are almost three times as likely to be shown a weapon as women are. The most popular form of force used by both men and women is verbal commands. The second most frequent form of force used against women is a takedown.Nearly every suspect, whether Black, White, or Hispanic, will have a weapon pointed at them; however, White and Black suspects are more likely to have verbal demands shouted at them. White and Black persons are more likely to hold down suspects, whereas suspects of Hispanic heritage are more likely to be grabbed. The most frequent form of force used on suspects who are White, Black, or Hispanic is a verbal demand.

Correlation Matrix


The correlation plot was created using 6 numerical columns. This includes “OFFICER_ID”,“SUBJECT_ID”,“REPORTING AREA”,“OFFICER_YEARS_ON_FORCE”,“STREET_NUMBER”,“STREET NUMBER”,“SECTOR”. According to the plot, “OFFICER_ID” and “OFFICER_YEARS_ON_FORCE” have a strong positive and negative correlation.
set.seed(1201)
sampleDataSet <- dallas[sample(nrow(dallas), 15), ]
# Convert relevant columns to numeric
sampleDataSet$OFFICER_ID <- as.numeric(sampleDataSet$OFFICER_ID)
sampleDataSet$SUBJECT_ID <- as.numeric(sampleDataSet$SUBJECT_ID)
sampleDataSet$REPORTING_AREA <- as.numeric(sampleDataSet$REPORTING_AREA)
sampleDataSet$OFFICER_YEARS_ON_FORCE <- as.numeric(sampleDataSet$OFFICER_YEARS_ON_FORCE)
sampleDataSet$STREET_NUMBER <- as.numeric(sampleDataSet$STREET_NUMBER)
sampleDataSet$SECTOR <- as.numeric(sampleDataSet$SECTOR)

# Calculate correlation matrix
correlation_matrix <- cor(sampleDataSet[, c("OFFICER_ID","SUBJECT_ID" ,"REPORTING_AREA", "OFFICER_YEARS_ON_FORCE","STREET_NUMBER", "SECTOR")])
pval.cor <- cor_pmat(correlation_matrix)
require(ggplot2); require(ggcorrplot); 
(G1 = ggcorrplot(correlation_matrix))

(G2 = ggcorrplot(correlation_matrix, hc.order = TRUE, type = "lower"))

(G3 = ggcorrplot(correlation_matrix, hc.order = TRUE, type = "upper"))

This report’s objective is to investigate the patterns and behaviour of police in Dallas, Texas, in 2016. The survey did reveal that black people were detained more frequently than other ethnic groups, but it’s crucial to emphasize that the reasons why this is the case were not examined.
